--- title: Makie aliases: - makie.html subtitle: A data visualization ecosystem for Julia author: Marie-HÃ©lÃ¨ne Burle --- :::{.def} There are several popular data visualization libraries for the Julia programming language (e.g. [Plots](https://github.com/JuliaPlots/Plots.jl), [Gadfly](https://github.com/GiovineItalia/Gadfly.jl), [VegaLite](https://github.com/queryverse/VegaLite.jl), [Makie](https://github.com/MakieOrg/Makie.jl)). They vary in their precompilation time, time to first plot, layout capabilities, ability to handle 3D data, ease of use, and syntax style. In this landscape, Makie focuses on high performance, fancy layouts, and extensibility. Makie comes with multiple backends. In this webinar, we will cover: - [GLMakie](https://docs.makie.org/stable/documentation/backends/glmakie/) (ideal for interactive 2D and 3D plotting) - [WGLMakie](https://docs.makie.org/stable/documentation/backends/wglmakie/) (an equivalent that runs within browsers) - [CairoMakie](https://docs.makie.org/stable/documentation/backends/cairomakie/) (best for high-quality vector graphics) We will also see how to run Makie in the Alliance clusters. ::: [Slides](wb_makie_slides.qmd){.btn .btn-outline-primary} [(Click and wait: this reveal.js presentation is heavy and takes some time to load.)]{.inlinenote}

{{< video https://www.youtube.com/embed/nmAv2bW9Y2I >}} ## Plotting in Julia There are many options to create plots in Julia. Some of the most popular ones are: - [Plots.jl](https://github.com/JuliaPlots/Plots.jl): high-level API for working with different back-ends (GR, Pyplot, Plotly...), - [PyPlot.jl](https://github.com/JuliaPy/PyPlot.jl): Julia interface to Matplotlib's `matplotlib.pyplot`, - [PlotlyJS.jl](https://github.com/JuliaPlots/PlotlyJS.jl): Julia interface to plotly.js, - [PlotlyLight.jl](https://github.com/JuliaComputing/PlotlyLight.jl): the fastest plotting option in Julia by far, but limited features, - [Gadfly.jl](https://github.com/GiovineItalia/Gadfly.jl): following the grammar of graphics popularized by Hadley Wickham in R, - [VegaLite.jl](https://github.com/queryverse/VegaLite.jl): grammar of interactive graphics, - [PGFPlotsX.jl](https://github.com/KristofferC/PGFPlotsX.jl): Julia interface to the PGFPlots LaTeX package, - [UnicodePlots.jl](https://github.com/JuliaPlots/UnicodePlots.jl): plots in the terminal ðŸ™‚, - [Makie.jl](https://github.com/MakieOrg/Makie.jl): powerful plotting ecosystem: animation, 3D, GPU optimization. This webinar focuses on [Makie.jl](https://github.com/MakieOrg/Makie.jl). ## The Makie ecosystem Makie consists of a core package (`Makie`), with the plots functionalities. In addition to this, a backend is needed to render plots into images or vector graphics. Three backends are available: - `CairoMakie`: vector graphics or high-quality 2D plots. Creates, but does not display plots (you need an IDE that does or you can use [ElectronDisplay.jl](https://github.com/queryverse/ElectronDisplay.jl)), - `GLMakie`: based on [OpenGL](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/OpenGL); 3D rendering and interactivity in [GLFW](https://www.glfw.org/) window (no vector graphics), - `WGLMakie`: web version of `GLMakie` (plots rendered in a browser instead of a window). ## Resources Here are some links and resources useful to get started with the Makie ecosystem: - [the official Makie documentation](https://docs.makie.org/stable/), - [Julia Data Science book, chapter 5](https://juliadatascience.io/DataVisualizationMakie), - the project [Beautiful Makie](https://github.com/MakieOrg/BeautifulMakie) contains many great plot examples, - cheatsheets: for 2D plotting: ![](img/makiecheatsheet2D.png){width=85%} :::{.caption} From: [Storopoli, Huijzer and Alonso (2021). Julia Data Science. https://juliadatascience.io. ISBN: 97984898](https://juliadatascience.io/datavisMakie_attributes) ::: for 3D plotting: ![](img/makiecheatsheet3D.png) :::{.caption} From: [Storopoli, Huijzer and Alonso (2021). Julia Data Science. https://juliadatascience.io. ISBN: 97984898](https://juliadatascience.io/datavisMakie_attributes) ::: ## Troubleshooting CairoMakie and WGLMakie should install without issues. Installing GLMakie however can be challenging. [This page](https://github.com/MakieOrg/Makie.jl/tree/master/GLMakie#troubleshooting-opengl) may lead you towards a solution. ## Extensions A number of extensions have been built on top of Makie: - [GeoMakie.jl](https://github.com/MakieOrg/GeoMakie.jl) add geographical plotting utilities to Makie, - [AlgebraOfGraphics.jl](https://github.com/MakieOrg/AlgebraOfGraphics.jl/) turns plotting into a simple algebra of building blocks, - [GraphMakie.jl](https://github.com/MakieOrg/GraphMakie.jl) to create network graphs. ## Fundamental functioning ### Figure Load the package (here, we are using CairoMakie): ::: {#124be065 .cell execution_count=2} ``` {.julia .cell-code} using CairoMakie # no need to import Makie itself ``` ::: Create a `Figure` (container object): ::: {#a65b9f14 .cell execution_count=3} ``` {.julia .cell-code} fig = Figure() ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stderr} ``` â”Œ Warning: Found `resolution` in the theme when creating a `Scene`. The `resolution` keyword for `Scene`s and `Figure`s has been deprecated. Use `Figure(; size = ...` or `Scene(; size = ...)` instead, which better reflects that this is a unitless size and not a pixel resolution. The key could also come from `set_theme!` calls or related theming functions. â”” @ Makie ~/.julia/packages/Makie/QGPt0/src/scenes.jl:220 ``` ::: ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=3} ![](wb_makie_files/figure-html/cell-3-output-2.svg){} ::: ::: ::: {#3be493f9 .cell execution_count=4} ``` {.julia .cell-code} typeof(fig) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=4} ``` Figure ``` ::: ::: You can customize a `Figure`: ::: {#461417b2 .cell execution_count=5} ``` {.julia .cell-code} fig2 = Figure(backgroundcolor=:grey22, resolution=(300, 300)) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stderr} ``` â”Œ Warning: Found `resolution` in the theme when creating a `Scene`. The `resolution` keyword for `Scene`s and `Figure`s has been deprecated. Use `Figure(; size = ...` or `Scene(; size = ...)` instead, which better reflects that this is a unitless size and not a pixel resolution. The key could also come from `set_theme!` calls or related theming functions. â”” @ Makie ~/.julia/packages/Makie/QGPt0/src/scenes.jl:220 ``` ::: ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=5} ![](wb_makie_files/figure-html/cell-5-output-2.svg){} ::: ::: Makie uses the [Colors.jl](https://github.com/JuliaGraphics/Colors.jl) package as a dependency. You can find a list of all named colours [here](https://juliagraphics.github.io/Colors.jl/stable/namedcolors/). To use CSS specification (e.g. hex), you need to install Colors explicitly and use [its color parsing capabilities](http://juliagraphics.github.io/Colors.jl/stable/constructionandconversion/#Color-Parsing): ::: {#cfb9f2f3 .cell execution_count=6} ``` {.julia .cell-code} using Colors fig3 = Figure(backgroundcolor=colorant"#adc2eb") ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stderr} ``` â”Œ Warning: Found `resolution` in the theme when creating a `Scene`. The `resolution` keyword for `Scene`s and `Figure`s has been deprecated. Use `Figure(; size = ...` or `Scene(; size = ...)` instead, which better reflects that this is a unitless size and not a pixel resolution. The key could also come from `set_theme!` calls or related theming functions. â”” @ Makie ~/.julia/packages/Makie/QGPt0/src/scenes.jl:220 ``` ::: ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=6} ![](wb_makie_files/figure-html/cell-6-output-2.svg){} ::: ::: ### Axis Then, you can create an `Axis`: ::: {#dab4202b .cell execution_count=7} ``` {.julia .cell-code} ax = Axis(Figure()[1, 1]) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stderr} ``` â”Œ Warning: Found `resolution` in the theme when creating a `Scene`. The `resolution` keyword for `Scene`s and `Figure`s has been deprecated. Use `Figure(; size = ...` or `Scene(; size = ...)` instead, which better reflects that this is a unitless size and not a pixel resolution. The key could also come from `set_theme!` calls or related theming functions. â”” @ Makie ~/.julia/packages/Makie/QGPt0/src/scenes.jl:220 ``` ::: ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=7} ``` Axis with 0 plots: ``` ::: ::: ::: {#7020de78 .cell execution_count=8} ``` {.julia .cell-code} typeof(ax) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=8} ``` Axis ``` ::: ::: ::: {#961a6c94 .cell execution_count=9} ``` {.julia .cell-code} Axis(fig3[1, 1]) # fig3[1, 1] sets the subplot layout: fig[row, col] fig3 ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=9} ![](wb_makie_files/figure-html/cell-9-output-1.svg){} ::: ::: ::: {#a67eddd6 .cell execution_count=10} ``` {.julia .cell-code} Axis(fig[2, 3]) # This is what happens if we change the layout fig ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=10} ![](wb_makie_files/figure-html/cell-10-output-1.svg){} ::: ::: ::: {#06c1c403 .cell execution_count=11} ``` {.julia .cell-code} Axis(fig3[2, 3]) # We can add another axis on fig3 fig3 ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=11} ![](wb_makie_files/figure-html/cell-11-output-1.svg){} ::: ::: Axis are customizable: ::: {#6b592f5b .cell execution_count=12} ``` {.julia .cell-code} fig4 = Figure() Axis(fig4[1, 1], xlabel="x label", ylabel="y label", title="Title of the plot") fig4 ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stderr} ``` â”Œ Warning: Found `resolution` in the theme when creating a `Scene`. The `resolution` keyword for `Scene`s and `Figure`s has been deprecated. Use `Figure(; size = ...` or `Scene(; size = ...)` instead, which better reflects that this is a unitless size and not a pixel resolution. The key could also come from `set_theme!` calls or related theming functions. â”” @ Makie ~/.julia/packages/Makie/QGPt0/src/scenes.jl:220 ``` ::: ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=12} ![](wb_makie_files/figure-html/cell-12-output-2.svg){} ::: ::: ### Plot Finally, you can add a plot: ::: {#cc3b9f7a .cell execution_count=13} ``` {.julia .cell-code} fig = Figure() ax = Axis(fig[1, 1]) x = LinRange(-10, 10, 20) y = x scatter!(ax, x, y) # Functions with ! transform their arguments fig ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stderr} ``` â”Œ Warning: Found `resolution` in the theme when creating a `Scene`. The `resolution` keyword for `Scene`s and `Figure`s has been deprecated. Use `Figure(; size = ...` or `Scene(; size = ...)` instead, which better reflects that this is a unitless size and not a pixel resolution. The key could also come from `set_theme!` calls or related theming functions. â”” @ Makie ~/.julia/packages/Makie/QGPt0/src/scenes.jl:220 ``` ::: ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=13} ![](wb_makie_files/figure-html/cell-13-output-2.svg){} ::: ::: Of course, there are many plotting functions, e.g. `scatterlines!`: ::: {#02342796 .cell execution_count=14} ``` {.julia .cell-code} fig = Figure() ax = Axis(fig[1, 1]) x = LinRange(-10, 10, 20) y = x scatterlines!(ax, x, y) # Functions with ! transform their arguments fig ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stderr} ``` â”Œ Warning: Found `resolution` in the theme when creating a `Scene`. The `resolution` keyword for `Scene`s and `Figure`s has been deprecated. Use `Figure(; size = ...` or `Scene(; size = ...)` instead, which better reflects that this is a unitless size and not a pixel resolution. The key could also come from `set_theme!` calls or related theming functions. â”” @ Makie ~/.julia/packages/Makie/QGPt0/src/scenes.jl:220 ``` ::: ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=14} ![](wb_makie_files/figure-html/cell-14-output-2.svg){} ::: ::: We can also use `lines!`: ::: {#6216a001 .cell execution_count=15} ``` {.julia .cell-code} fig = Figure() ax = Axis(fig[1, 1]) x = LinRange(-10, 10, 20) y = sin.(x) # The . means that the function is broadcast to each element of x lines!(ax, x, y) fig ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stderr} ``` â”Œ Warning: Found `resolution` in the theme when creating a `Scene`. Use `Figure(; size = ...` or `Scene(; size = ...)` instead, which better reflects that this is a unitless size and not a pixel resolution. The key could also come from `set_theme!` calls or related theming functions. â”” @ Makie ~/.julia/packages/Makie/QGPt0/src/scenes.jl:220 ``` ::: ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=15} ![](wb_makie_files/figure-html/cell-15-output-2.svg){} ::: ::: Let's add points to get a smoother line: ::: {#15cb6209 .cell execution_count=16} ``` {.julia .cell-code} fig = Figure() ax = Axis(fig[1, 1]) x = LinRange(-10, 10, 1000) y = sin.(x) # The . means that the function is broadcast to each element of x lines!(ax, x, y) fig ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stderr} ``` â”Œ Warning: Found `resolution` in the theme when creating a `Scene`. The `resolution` keyword for `Scene`s and `Figure`s has been deprecated. Use `Figure(; size = ...` or `Scene(; size = ...)` instead, which better reflects that this is a unitless size and not a pixel resolution. The key could also come from `set_theme!` calls or related theming functions. â”” @ Makie ~/.julia/packages/Makie/QGPt0/src/scenes.jl:220 ``` ::: ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=16} ![](wb_makie_files/figure-html/cell-16-output-2.svg){} ::: ::: Now, you don't have to create the `Figure`, `Axis`, and plot one at a time. You can create them at the same time with, for instance `lines`: ::: {#48868143 .cell execution_count=17} ``` {.julia .cell-code} x = LinRange(-10, 10, 1000) y = sin.(x) lines(x, y) # Note the use of lines instead of lines! ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stderr} ``` â”Œ Warning: Found `resolution` in the theme when creating a `Scene`. The `resolution` keyword for `Scene`s and `Figure`s has been deprecated. Use `Figure(; size = ...` or `Scene(; size = ...)` instead, which better reflects that this is a unitless size and not a pixel resolution. The key could also come from `set_theme!` calls or related theming functions. â”” @ Makie ~/.julia/packages/Makie/QGPt0/src/scenes.jl:220 ``` ::: ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=17} ![](wb_makie_files/figure-html/cell-17-output-2.svg){} ::: ::: Or even more simply: ::: {#91f71b07 .cell execution_count=18} ``` {.julia .cell-code} x = LinRange(-10, 10, 1000) lines(x, sin) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stderr} ``` â”Œ Warning: Found `resolution` in the theme when creating a `Scene`. Use `Figure(; size = ...` or `Scene(; size = ...)` instead, which better reflects that this is a unitless size and not a pixel resolution. The key could also come from `set_theme!` calls or related theming functions. â”” @ Makie ~/.julia/packages/Makie/QGPt0/src/scenes.jl:220 ``` ::: ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=18} ![](wb_makie_files/figure-html/cell-18-output-2.svg){} ::: ::: This is a lot simpler, but it is important to understand the concepts of the `Figure` and `Axis` objects as you will need it to customize them: ::: {#ee4e08c2 .cell execution_count=19} ``` {.julia .cell-code} x = LinRange(-10, 10, 1000) y = cos.(x) lines(x, y; figure=(; backgroundcolor=:green), axis=(; title="Cosinus function", xlabel="x label", ylabel="y label")) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stderr} ``` â”Œ Warning: Found `resolution` in the theme when creating a `Scene`. The `resolution` keyword for `Scene`s and `Figure`s has been deprecated. Use `Figure(; size = ...` or `Scene(; size = ...)` instead, which better reflects that this is a unitless size and not a pixel resolution. The key could also come from `set_theme!` calls or related theming functions. â”” @ Makie ~/.julia/packages/Makie/QGPt0/src/scenes.jl:220 ``` ::: ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=19} ![](wb_makie_files/figure-html/cell-19-output-2.svg){} ::: ::: When you create the `Figure`, `Axis`, and plot at the same time, you create a `FigureAxisPlot` object: ::: {#375f2de4 .cell execution_count=20} ``` {.julia .cell-code} x = LinRange(-10, 10, 1000) y = cos.(x) obj = lines(x, y; figure=(; backgroundcolor=:green), axis=(; title="Cosinus function", xlabel="x label", ylabel="y label")); typeof(obj) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stderr} ``` â”Œ Warning: Found `resolution` in the theme when creating a `Scene`. This is because these are one-element NamedTuples. ::: The mutating functions (with `!`) can be used to add plots to an existing figure, but first, you need to decompose the `FigureAxisPlot` object: ::: {#d2defc19 .cell execution_count=21} ``` {.julia .cell-code} fig, ax, plot = lines(x, sin) lines!(ax, x, cos) # Remember that we are transforming the Axis object fig # Now we can plot the transformed Figure ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stderr} ``` â”Œ Warning: Found `resolution` in the theme when creating a `Scene`. The `resolution` keyword for `Scene`s and `Figure`s has been deprecated. Use `Figure(; size = ...` or `Scene(; size = ...)` instead, which better reflects that this is a unitless size and not a pixel resolution. The key could also come from `set_theme!` calls or related theming functions. â”” @ Makie ~/.julia/packages/Makie/QGPt0/src/scenes.jl:220 ``` ::: ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=21} ![](wb_makie_files/figure-html/cell-21-output-2.svg){} ::: ::: Or we can add several plots on different `Axis` in the same `Figure`: ::: {#ffbf74d4 .cell execution_count=22} ``` {.julia .cell-code} fig, ax1, plot = lines(x, sin) ax2 = Axis(fig[1, 2]) lines!(ax2, x, cos) fig ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stderr} ``` â”Œ Warning: Found `resolution` in the theme when creating a `Scene`. The `resolution` keyword for `Scene`s and `Figure`s has been deprecated. Use `Figure(; size = ...` or `Scene(; size = ...)` instead, which better reflects that this is a unitless size and not a pixel resolution. The key could also come from `set_theme!` calls or related theming functions. â”” @ Makie ~/.julia/packages/Makie/QGPt0/src/scenes.jl:220 ``` ::: ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=22} ![](wb_makie_files/figure-html/cell-22-output-2.svg){} ::: ::: ## Examples ### 2D ::: {#9362d2a3 .cell execution_count=23} ``` {.julia .cell-code} using CairoMakie using StatsBase, LinearAlgebra using Interpolations, OnlineStats using Distributions CairoMakie.activate!(type = "png") function eq_hist(matrix; nbins = 256 * 256) h_eq = fit(Histogram, vec(matrix), nbins = nbins) h_eq = normalize(h_eq, mode = :density) cdf = cumsum(h_eq.weights) cdf = cdf / cdf[end] edg = h_eq.edges[1] interp_linear = LinearInterpolation(edg, [cdf..., cdf[end]]) out = reshape(interp_linear(vec(matrix)), size(matrix)) return out end function getcounts!(h, fn; n = 100) for _ in 1:n vals = eigvals(fn()) x0 = real.(vals) y0 = imag.(vals) fit!(h, zip(x0,y0)) end end m(;a=10rand()-5, b=10rand()-5) = [0 0 0 a; -1 -1 1 0; b 0 0 0; -1 -1 -1 -1] h = HeatMap(range(-3.5,3.5,length=1200), range(-3.5,3.5, length=1200)) getcounts!(h, m; n=2_000_000) with_theme(theme_black()) do fig = Figure(figure_padding=0,resolution=(600,600)) ax = Axis(fig[1,1]; aspect = DataAspect()) heatmap!(ax,-3.5..3.5, -3.5..3.5, eq_hist(h.counts); colormap = :bone_1) hidedecorations!(ax) hidespines!(ax) fig end ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stderr} ``` Precompiling OnlineStats âœ“ OnlineStatsBase âœ“ OnlineStats 2 dependencies successfully precompiled in 3 seconds. 48 already precompiled. â”Œ Warning: Found `resolution` in the theme when creating a `Scene`. The `resolution` keyword for `Scene`s and `Figure`s has been deprecated. Use `Figure(; size = ...` or `Scene(; size = ...)` instead, which better reflects that this is a unitless size and not a pixel resolution. The key could also come from `set_theme!` calls or related theming functions. â”” @ Makie ~/.julia/packages/Makie/QGPt0/src/scenes.jl:220 ``` ::: ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=23} ```{=html} ``` ::: ::: ### 3D ```{.julia} using GLMakie, Random GLMakie.activate!() Random.seed!(13) x = -6:0.5:6 y = -6:0.5:6 z = 6exp.( -(x.^2 .+ y' .^ 2)./4) box = Rect3(Point3f(-0.5), Vec3f(1)) n = 100 g(x) = x^(1/10) alphas = [g(x) for x in range(0,1,length=n)] cmap_alpha = resample_cmap(:linear_worb_100_25_c53_n256, n, alpha = alphas) with_theme(theme_dark()) do fig, ax, = meshscatter(x, y, z; marker=box, markersize = 0.5, color = vec(z), colormap = cmap_alpha, colorrange = (0,6), axis = (; type = Axis3, aspect = :data, azimuth = 7.3, elevation = 0.189, perspectiveness = 0.5), figure = (; resolution =(1200,800))) meshscatter!(ax, x .+ 7, y, z./2; markersize = 0.25, color = vec(z./2), colormap = cmap_alpha, colorrange = (0, 6), ambient = Vec3f(0.85, 0.85, 0.85), backlight = 1.5f0) xlims!(-5.5,10) ylims!(-5.5,5.5) hidedecorations!(ax; grid = false) hidespines!(ax) fig end ``` ![](img/makie_plot.jpg) :::{.note} For more examples, have a look at [Beautiful Makie](https://github.com/MakieOrg/BeautifulMakie). ::: ## Compiling sysimages While Makie is extremely powerful, its compilation time and its time to first plot are extremely long. For this reason, it might save you a lot of time to create a sysimage (a file containing information from a Julia session such as loaded packages, global variables, compiled code, etc.) with [PackageCompiler.jl](https://github.com/JuliaLang/PackageCompiler.jl). :::{.note} The upcoming Julia 1.9 will do this automatically. ::: ## Using the Alliance clusters ### CairoMakie CairoMakie will run without problem on the Alliance clusters. It is not designed for interactivity, so saving to file is what makes the most sense. :::{.example} Example: ::: ```{.julia} save("graph.png", fig) ``` :::{.note} Remember however that CairoMakie is 2D only (for now). ::: ### GLMakie GLMakie relies on [GLFW](https://www.glfw.org/) to create windows with OpenGL. GLFW doesn't support creating contexts without an associated window. The dependency [GLFW.jl](https://github.com/JuliaGL/GLFW.jl) will thus not install in the clustersâ€”even with X11 forwardingâ€”unless you use [VDI nodes](https://docs.alliancecan.ca/wiki/VNC#VDI_Nodes), [VNC](https://docs.alliancecan.ca/wiki/VNC), or [Virtual GL](https://virtualgl.org/). ### WGLMakie You can setup a server with [JSServe.jl](https://github.com/SimonDanisch/JSServe.jl) as per [the documentation](http://juliaplots.org/WGLMakie.jl/stable/). However, this method is intended for the creation of interactive widgets, e.g. for a website. While this is really cool, it isn't optimized for performance. There might also be a way to create an SSH tunnel to your local browser, although there is no documentation on this. Best probably is to save to file. :::{.info} **Conclusion about the Makie ecosystem on production clusters:** - 2D plots: use CairoMakie and save to file, - 3D plots: use WGLMakie and save to file. :::
